('climate-corp', 'Climate Corporation', 'AI-powered digital agriculture platform for field-level crop monitoring and agronomic recommendations',
 E'Climate Corporation, now operating under the Climate FieldView brand and owned by Bayer, is the leading digital agriculture platform for row crop farmers in North America. The platform ingests field-level data from a wide range of sources - planting maps, soil sampling, rainfall data, satellite imagery, and yield monitor data - and uses AI to generate agronomic recommendations specific to each individual field. Rather than giving generic regional advice, Climate FieldView analyzes what actually happened in each field historically and recommends seeding rates, fertilizer prescriptions, and management practices optimized for each field''s unique conditions.\n\nThe platform''s field-level insights are built on a dataset representing hundreds of millions of acres of actual field performance data across North American growing seasons - one of the largest proprietary agricultural datasets in existence. AI models trained on this data can predict yield potential by field zone, identify areas of a field where inputs are being over- or under-applied, and recommend variable rate prescriptions that match input levels to actual field productivity potential. Integration with major farm equipment brands including John Deere, Case IH, and CNH Industrial allows prescriptions to flow directly to the tractor display for automated application.\n\nFor corn and soybean growers operating at any scale, Climate FieldView provides the data infrastructure to move from calendar-based farming to data-driven agronomic decision making. The platform also includes a carbon program that pays growers for adopting sustainable practices and documenting them through the FieldView data pipeline. As Bayer''s digital agriculture flagship, FieldView connects into Bayer''s Crop Science product portfolio for seed selection and crop protection recommendations.',
 'https://climate.com', 'https://climate.com',
 'freemium', true, 0, 4.2, 3100, false, true, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'precision-agriculture', 'data-analytics'],
 ARRAY['Field-level AI recommendations built on hundreds of millions of acres of actual performance data', 'Variable rate prescription generation flows directly to John Deere, Case IH, and CNH equipment', 'Free basic tier gives farmers data capture without subscription cost', 'Carbon program pays growers for sustainable practice documentation through the data pipeline'],
 ARRAY['Most value for corn and soybean row crop farmers - less relevant for specialty or horticultural crops', 'Bayer ownership creates real or perceived conflict of interest in seed and chemistry recommendations', 'Free tier has limited analysis features - full AI recommendations require paid FieldView Plus', 'Data sharing terms require careful review - farm data feeds Bayer''s broader research dataset'],
 ARRAY['Variable rate seeding and fertilizer prescriptions optimized to individual field zones', 'Multi-year field performance benchmarking to identify underperforming areas and management causes', 'Carbon credit enrollment and practice documentation for row crop sustainability programs'],
 NOW()),

('john-deere-ai', 'John Deere AI', 'Autonomous farming platform combining See & Spray precision weed control and AI-guided autonomous tractors',
 E'John Deere''s AI and autonomy platform represents the most commercially deployed precision agriculture technology in the world, combining the See & Spray targeted herbicide application system, the Operations Center farm management platform, and an expanding portfolio of autonomous and semi-autonomous tractor capabilities. See & Spray uses computer vision and AI to distinguish between crops and weeds in real time at planting speed, applying herbicide only to weeds rather than the entire field - reducing herbicide use by up to 77 percent in trials while maintaining equivalent weed control. The technology is available as a factory-installed option on John Deere sprayers and as an aftermarket upgrade for existing equipment.\n\nJohn Deere''s Operations Center is the farm management backbone connecting machine data, field records, agronomic recommendations, and precision application maps across an entire farming operation. The platform ingests data from every John Deere machine on the farm - tractors, planters, combines, sprayers - and provides a unified view of field-by-field performance, machine utilization, and input application. AI models analyze this data to surface agronomic insights, flag anomalies in yield data, and generate prescription recommendations that integrate with the precision application capabilities on John Deere equipment.\n\nThe autonomous tractor program, initiated with the 8R series, provides hands-free field operation for soil preparation tasks - allowing operators to supervise multiple machines remotely while they perform precise autonomous field passes. For large row crop and grain operations that want to reduce labor dependence, improve application precision, and capture the operational efficiency gains from AI-guided farming, John Deere''s integrated AI and autonomy stack represents the most proven commercial option in 2026.',
 'https://deere.com/en/technology-products/precision-ag-technology/', 'https://deere.com',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.4, 4700, false, true, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'precision-agriculture', 'autonomous-systems'],
 ARRAY['See & Spray reduces herbicide use up to 77% with real-time crop vs weed computer vision', 'Operations Center unifies all machine data, field records, and prescriptions in one platform', 'Autonomous 8R tractor enables hands-free field operation for labor reduction on large operations', 'Broadest equipment integration ecosystem - works natively with most John Deere machinery in the field'],
 ARRAY['Full AI and autonomy capabilities require purchasing new John Deere equipment or expensive retrofits', 'Operations Center is most valuable for all-John Deere equipment fleets - mixed fleets have integration gaps', 'See & Spray commercial availability is currently limited to cotton and certain row crop configurations', 'Data is stored on John Deere''s platform - farm data portability and ownership terms require review'],
 ARRAY['Precision herbicide application using real-time plant identification to cut input costs on large acreage', 'Autonomous field preparation and soil tillage operations for labor-constrained large grain farms', 'Fleet-wide agronomic data analysis and prescription generation for multi-farm enterprise management'],
 NOW()),

('indigo-agriculture', 'Indigo Agriculture', 'Biological seed treatments and AI-powered carbon marketplace connecting farmers to sustainability markets',
 E'Indigo Agriculture combines two distinct value propositions: a biological seed treatment platform that uses beneficial microbes to improve crop resilience and yield, and an AI-powered carbon and sustainability marketplace that connects farmers to buyers of carbon credits, soil health outcomes, and sustainably produced grain. The company is unusual in the agritech landscape because it operates simultaneously as a crop science company and as a data and financial services platform connecting agricultural producers to premium markets.\n\nIndigo''s Biological division applies microbial seed treatments - formulations of beneficial soil bacteria and fungi that colonize plant roots - to enhance crop performance under stress conditions including drought, high temperatures, and nutrient-limited soils. The treatments are applied to seed at planting and are designed to complement rather than replace chemical inputs, improving the efficiency of fertilizer and water use. Field trial data across multiple crops and geographies has demonstrated yield improvements in the range of 3-8 percent under stress conditions, with variable results depending on local soil microbiome conditions.\n\nThe Indigo Carbon marketplace is the platform''s more commercially significant innovation. Using satellite imagery, soil sampling, and practice verification data collected through the Indigo platform, farmers can document the adoption of regenerative practices - cover cropping, reduced tillage, improved nutrient management - and receive payments from corporate buyers purchasing carbon credits or sustainability-linked grain premiums. For farmers exploring carbon markets, Indigo provides both the measurement and monitoring infrastructure and the buyer network that makes converting sustainable practices into revenue practical.',
 'https://www.indigoag.com', 'https://www.indigoag.com',
 'freemium', true, 0, 3.9, 1240, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'sustainability', 'precision-agriculture'],
 ARRAY['Carbon marketplace connects farmers directly to corporate buyers without broker intermediaries', 'Biological treatments work alongside existing chemistry programs - additive not disruptive to current practice', 'Practice verification uses satellite and sensor data - reduces farmer documentation burden for carbon programs', 'Indigo Marketplace provides premium grain marketing options beyond commodity price'],
 ARRAY['Carbon credit prices and program terms have fluctuated - farmer payments are not guaranteed income', 'Biological treatment performance is highly variable by soil type, geography, and growing season conditions', 'Carbon program enrollment requirements may conflict with some existing farm management practices', 'Company financial stability has been a concern - Indigo has undergone significant restructuring since 2022'],
 ARRAY['Carbon credit enrollment and monitoring for row crop farms adopting regenerative practices', 'Biological seed treatment programs to improve drought and heat stress resilience in corn and soy', 'Premium grain marketing through Indigo Marketplace for farmers targeting sustainability-linked buyers'],
 NOW()),

('granular', 'Granular', 'Agri-business management platform for farm financial tracking, workforce management, and operational analytics',
 E'Granular, owned by Corteva Agriscience, is an agri-business management platform designed specifically for the operational and financial management needs of commercial-scale farming operations. Unlike precision agriculture platforms focused on agronomic recommendations and field data, Granular addresses the business management side of farming: tracking costs by field and enterprise, managing farm labor and equipment utilization, budgeting and cash flow forecasting, and generating the financial reporting that farm lenders and landowners require.\n\nThe platform''s field-level cost tracking is the core differentiator. Granular allows farm operators to allocate every input cost - seed, fertilizer, chemicals, labor, custom work - to individual fields and crop enterprises, providing accurate cost-of-production data at the field level rather than farm-wide averages. This granularity enables farmers to identify unprofitable fields, optimize land rental decisions, and calculate true break-even prices for commodity marketing decisions. AI features include automated cost categorization from invoices and receipts, production benchmarking against regional peers, and cash flow forecasting based on current crop prices and production cost projections.\n\nGranular integrates with Climate FieldView, John Deere Operations Center, and major farm accounting systems including QuickBooks and AgriFinancials, positioning it as the financial and operational layer in a broader precision agriculture technology stack. Corteva''s ownership provides integration with Pioneer seed data and Corteva crop protection programs. For large commercial operations - typically 1,000+ acres - where understanding profitability at the field level is the difference between viable and marginal operations, Granular provides the financial intelligence that spreadsheets cannot scale to deliver.',
 'https://granular.ag', 'https://granular.ag',
 'paid', false, 59, 4.1, 980, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'business-management', 'analytics'],
 ARRAY['Field-level cost tracking allocates every input to individual fields for accurate cost-of-production', 'Integrates with Climate FieldView, John Deere Operations Center, and farm accounting systems', 'Labor and equipment management designed for the seasonal and task-based nature of farm workforces', 'Corteva ownership provides seed and crop protection integration for Pioneer seed customers'],
 ARRAY['Primarily designed for large commercial row crop operations - less suited to specialty crops or small farms', 'Learning curve is significant for farm operators without prior experience in farm management software', 'Corteva ownership may bias recommendations toward Pioneer and Corteva products', 'Pricing at $59+ per month requires justification for operations under 500 acres'],
 ARRAY['Field-level profitability analysis to identify underperforming land and optimize rental rates', 'Seasonal cash flow forecasting using actual field costs and current commodity price scenarios', 'Farm labor and equipment scheduling and cost tracking across multi-farm enterprise operations'],
 NOW()),

('taranis', 'Taranis', 'AI crop intelligence platform using ultra-high-resolution aerial imaging for field-level pest and disease detection',
 E'Taranis is a precision agriculture platform built around ultra-high-resolution aerial imaging and AI analysis for early detection of crop stress, pest pressure, and disease outbreaks at the sub-inch resolution level. The platform operates through a combination of fixed-wing aircraft, drones, and satellite imagery processed through computer vision models trained on millions of annotated crop imagery samples across major row crops worldwide. The AI can identify specific pest species, disease symptoms, and nutrient deficiency patterns at a resolution that satellite imagery cannot match and that human scouting cannot cover cost-effectively at scale.\n\nThe core use case is replacing or augmenting physical crop scouting with automated aerial surveillance that covers entire fields multiple times per season. Agronomists and crop advisors use Taranis to prioritize their physical scouting time on the areas of highest concern identified by AI analysis, rather than walking fields on a calendar schedule. The platform generates automatically prioritized field alerts with GPS-located images of detected issues, allowing agronomists serving large acreage to respond to crop problems days earlier than traditional scouting would enable.\n\nTaranis has been deployed at scale by large row crop farmers, crop consultants serving multi-farm clients, and seed companies conducting research trials requiring systematic early-season crop assessment. The platform integrates with Climate FieldView, John Deere Operations Center, and major agronomic software platforms to route alerts into existing farm management workflows. For professional crop advisors and large-scale farm operators in corn, soybeans, wheat, and cotton, Taranis provides pest and disease intelligence that justifies input spend and reduces yield loss from late-detected stress events.',
 'https://taranis.ag', 'https://taranis.ag',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.3, 720, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'precision-agriculture', 'computer-vision'],
 ARRAY['Sub-inch resolution aerial imaging detects pest and disease issues at a level satellite imagery cannot match', 'AI analysis across millions of annotated samples provides high-accuracy identification of specific pest species', 'Automated field alerts prioritize agronomist attention on highest-concern areas rather than calendar scouting', 'Integrates with Climate FieldView and John Deere Operations Center for workflow-integrated pest management'],
 ARRAY['Pricing is not publicly listed - requires engagement with sales team for custom quotes', 'Coverage depends on aerial imaging flight scheduling - not always available for immediate urgent needs', 'Most valuable for large row crop operations - ROI is harder to justify for smaller farms', 'AI accuracy varies by crop type and region - performance is best documented for corn, soybeans, and wheat'],
 ARRAY['Early-season pest and disease detection to enable timely targeted intervention before yield loss', 'Crop scouting prioritization for agronomists serving large multi-farm advisory territory', 'Research trial assessment for seed companies requiring systematic field-level crop monitoring at scale'],
 NOW()),

('awhere', 'aWhere', 'Hyperlocal weather intelligence and agronomic analytics platform for data-driven crop management decisions',
 E'aWhere provides hyperlocal weather intelligence and agronomic data services for agricultural enterprises, commodity traders, NGOs, and development organizations operating in markets where traditional weather data infrastructure is sparse or unreliable. The platform''s core capability is building accurate weather models for specific geographic locations using a combination of ground station networks, remote sensing data, and sophisticated interpolation algorithms - providing daily temperature, precipitation, humidity, and evapotranspiration data at resolutions as fine as 9 kilometers even in areas with no weather station coverage.\n\nFor agricultural decision making, aWhere''s agronomic analytics layer translates raw weather data into agronomically meaningful metrics: growing degree day accumulation for crop phenology tracking, evapotranspiration for irrigation scheduling, chill hour accumulation for deciduous fruit crops, and disease pressure models that use temperature and humidity data to predict outbreak risk for major fungal and bacterial pathogens. The historical weather database spanning 30+ years allows benchmarking of current-season conditions against long-term averages, helping farmers and agronomists understand whether current conditions represent genuine anomalies or normal year-to-year variability.\n\nAWhere is particularly valuable in emerging market agricultural contexts where commercial weather services designed for high-income country markets do not provide usable coverage. Development organizations and NGOs use aWhere to support smallholder farmers in Sub-Saharan Africa, South Asia, and Latin America with weather-informed agronomic advice delivered through mobile extension services. Commercial agricultural enterprises use the API to incorporate hyperlocal weather intelligence into their own decision-support tools, trading algorithms, and supply chain risk models.',
 'https://www.awhere.com', 'https://www.awhere.com',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.0, 410, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'data-analytics', 'precision-agriculture'],
 ARRAY['Hyperlocal 9km resolution weather data covers regions with no ground station infrastructure', '30+ year historical weather database enables long-term agronomic benchmarking', 'Agronomic analytics translate weather data into actionable crop management metrics', 'API-first design integrates weather intelligence into third-party agricultural platforms'],
 ARRAY['Pricing requires sales engagement - no self-serve tier for individual farmers', 'Platform is designed for enterprises and organizations - not optimized for direct farmer use', 'Data accuracy in extremely remote regions with no nearby ground stations is lower than marketed areas', 'Agronomic models are strongest for major commodity crops - specialty crop support varies'],
 ARRAY['Irrigation scheduling and water management decisions using evapotranspiration and soil moisture modeling', 'Disease pressure forecasting for fungal and bacterial pathogens based on temperature and humidity windows', 'Emerging market agricultural extension programs delivering weather-informed advice to smallholder farmers'],
 NOW()),

('prospera', 'Prospera Technologies', 'AI-driven crop monitoring and irrigation management platform for high-value fruit and vegetable growers',
 E'Prospera Technologies, acquired by Valmont Industries in 2022, provides AI-powered crop monitoring and irrigation management specifically for high-value specialty crop production - table grapes, almonds, tomatoes, peppers, and other fruits and vegetables where the economics of early problem detection and precise irrigation management justify significant per-acre investment in monitoring technology. The platform combines in-field sensors, computer vision cameras mounted on irrigation equipment, and satellite imagery processed through crop-specific AI models to provide continuous crop health monitoring and irrigation recommendations.\n\nThe computer vision component is the most technically distinctive capability. Cameras mounted on irrigation center pivots or other field equipment capture images of the crop canopy as irrigation equipment moves through the field. AI models analyze these images to detect early-stage disease symptoms, nutrient deficiency signatures, pest damage, and water stress indicators that are not visible to the naked eye until problems become severe. The system generates field maps showing the spatial distribution of detected crop stress, allowing targeted treatment of affected areas rather than field-wide application.\n\nProspera''s irrigation management module integrates with variable-rate irrigation controllers on center pivots and drip irrigation systems, allowing the platform to generate and execute precision irrigation prescriptions based on crop water demand modeling that incorporates weather data, soil sensor readings, and crop growth stage. For high-value specialty crop growers where water costs and crop quality premiums both justify precision agriculture investment, Prospera provides monitoring and decision support that reduces labor costs for scouting while improving the timeliness of crop management responses.',
 'https://prospera.ag', 'https://prospera.ag',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.1, 560, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'precision-agriculture', 'computer-vision'],
 ARRAY['Computer vision cameras on irrigation equipment provide continuous crop canopy monitoring without additional scouting labor', 'Early disease and stress detection enables targeted treatment before problems spread across the field', 'Variable-rate irrigation integration enables precision water management for water-limited production regions', 'Specialty crop focus means AI models are trained on the crops and conditions relevant to fruit and vegetable growers'],
 ARRAY['Acquired by Valmont in 2022 - product roadmap and support quality subject to corporate integration decisions', 'Hardware installation on irrigation equipment requires investment beyond software subscription', 'Most relevant for irrigated high-value crops - limited applicability for dryland row crop or grain farming', 'Integration with non-Valmont irrigation equipment may have limitations'],
 ARRAY['Automated crop health monitoring for high-value specialty crops to reduce scouting labor costs', 'Early disease and pest detection in table grapes, almonds, and processed tomatoes before yield loss', 'Precision irrigation management to optimize water use in drought-affected or water-limited production regions'],
 NOW()),

('farmers-business-network', 'Farmers Business Network', 'Data-driven agricultural cooperative for seed, chemical, and input procurement at below-retail prices',
 E'Farmers Business Network (FBN) is a farmer cooperative and data platform that uses aggregated farm performance data to provide members with buying power in seed and chemical procurement, access to transparent pricing information, and agronomic insights derived from the collective performance of millions of acres of member farms. The platform''s core premise is that farmers operating as individual buyers pay manufacturer list prices for inputs while large agricultural retailers capture the margin between true cost and retail. By aggregating purchasing across a network of member farms, FBN negotiates direct manufacturer relationships that reduce input costs for members.\n\nThe data platform collects anonymized field performance data - yield maps, planting records, input applications - from member farms and uses AI to identify which seed varieties and input programs perform best in specific soil types, geographies, and growing conditions. Members can query this performance database to make seed selection decisions informed by actual field results from similar farms in their region rather than relying solely on university trial data or seed company marketing. The seed performance comparison tool has been particularly adopted by farmers seeking unbiased alternatives to seed company-controlled trial data.\n\nFBN''s F2F Genetics Network provides direct access to seed genetics at below-brand-name prices, giving members the option to test genetics that perform comparably to major brands at lower per-unit cost. The platform also offers crop insurance, fuel, and financial services through an expanding suite of farmer-facing products. With over 50,000 member farms representing hundreds of millions of acres, FBN has built one of the largest independent agricultural performance datasets outside of the major seed and chemical companies.',
 'https://www.fbn.com', 'https://www.fbn.com',
 'freemium', true, 0, 4.3, 2890, false, true, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'precision-agriculture', 'business-management'],
 ARRAY['Data from 50,000+ member farms provides unbiased seed performance benchmarking by soil type and geography', 'Input pricing transparency reveals actual cost vs retail markup for seed and chemical purchases', 'F2F Genetics Network provides access to below-brand seed genetics for cost-conscious growers', 'Free membership tier provides basic pricing and data access without commitment'],
 ARRAY['Full benefit requires data contribution - members who don''t share field data get less from the network', 'Most valuable for corn, soy, and wheat row crop farmers - smaller benefit for specialty crop producers', 'Seed genetics from F2F Network may not yet have the regional performance depth of major brands in all geographies', 'Some farmers have concerns about data sharing with a network that competes with their existing supplier relationships'],
 ARRAY['Seed performance benchmarking using member farm data to make variety selection decisions without brand bias', 'Input cost reduction through cooperative procurement and transparent pricing for seed and crop protection', 'Crop insurance and financial services access through a farmer-aligned cooperative structure'],
 NOW()),

('blue-river-technology', 'Blue River Technology', 'AI-powered See & Spray precision weed control technology for sustainable input reduction',
 E'Blue River Technology, a John Deere subsidiary acquired in 2017, pioneered the See & Spray technology that uses computer vision and machine learning to identify individual plants in a field and apply herbicide only to weeds rather than broadcasting chemical across the entire crop canopy. The system operates in real time at field sprayer speeds, processing camera images at rates that allow individual plant identification and targeted spray nozzle activation with precision measured in centimeters. The result is herbicide use reduction of 50-90 percent depending on weed pressure, with equivalent weed control efficacy compared to blanket application.\n\nBlue River''s core contribution is the computer vision pipeline that makes real-time plant identification practical at field scale. The AI was trained on millions of labeled plant images across the major weed species and crop types common in US row crop agriculture. The system distinguishes between crop plants and weeds even in dense canopy conditions, at varying crop growth stages, and under different lighting conditions. This training depth is what separates See & Spray from less proven alternatives - the models have been validated across commercial-scale deployments on millions of acres.\n\nAs a John Deere subsidiary, Blue River''s technology is commercially available as the See & Spray feature on John Deere ExactApply sprayers and as a factory-installed option on select cotton and corn production equipment. The technology''s environmental and economic benefits have attracted attention from regulators, agrochemical companies, and sustainability-focused food and beverage companies interested in reducing herbicide use in their supply chains. For growers facing herbicide resistance management challenges or sustainability commitments that require demonstrable input reduction, See & Spray represents the most commercially proven precision herbicide application technology available.',
 'https://bluerivertechnology.com', 'https://bluerivertechnology.com',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.4, 890, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'computer-vision', 'precision-agriculture'],
 ARRAY['Real-time plant-level herbicide application reduces chemical use 50-90% vs broadcast spraying', 'AI trained on millions of labeled plant images provides reliable weed detection across major US crop types', 'Commercial-scale validation across millions of acres provides real performance data beyond laboratory trials', 'Environmental and sustainability credentials support grower compliance with retailer sustainability commitments'],
 ARRAY['Technology is available only through John Deere equipment - not accessible on non-Deere sprayers', 'See & Spray adds significant cost premium to new John Deere sprayer purchase or retrofit', 'Currently validated primarily for US row crop weed species - broader international crop coverage is expanding', 'Retrofit availability for existing sprayer fleets is limited compared to factory-installed new equipment option'],
 ARRAY['Herbicide use reduction and resistance management for farms with documented weed resistance challenges', 'Sustainability reporting and supply chain documentation for food companies requiring herbicide use metrics', 'Cost-of-production reduction through targeted herbicide application on large acreage corn and cotton farms'],
 NOW()),

('agworld', 'Agworld', 'Farm collaboration platform for agronomists, growers, and advisors to share agronomic data and recommendations',
 E'Agworld is a farm collaboration and agronomic data management platform designed to improve communication and data sharing between growers, crop advisors, agronomists, and agricultural retailers. Where most precision agriculture platforms are built around equipment data and field sensors, Agworld focuses on the advisory relationship - creating a shared digital workspace where the agronomist''s recommendations, field observations, input applications, and crop monitoring notes are recorded in a format that both the advisor and the grower can access and act on.\n\nThe platform''s core workflow is built around the agronomist''s scouting and recommendation cycle. Crop advisors use the mobile app to record field observations with GPS location, capture photos of pest or disease issues, log scouting data, and generate treatment recommendations that are immediately shared with the grower. Growers receive real-time notifications of advisor recommendations and can approve, question, or act on them without waiting for paper reports or phone calls. The shared record creates a documented history of all agronomic decisions made on each field across multiple seasons.\n\nAgworld integrates with aerial imagery from drones and satellites, laboratory soil testing services, and farm accounting systems to create a comprehensive agronomic record alongside the advisory communication layer. For agricultural retailers and crop consulting businesses managing advisory relationships across dozens to hundreds of farms, Agworld provides the workflow and data management infrastructure that separates professional consulting operations from informal knowledge sharing. The platform has been widely adopted in Australian and US broadacre farming operations, as well as specialty and horticultural enterprises where advisor-grower communication frequency is high.',
 'https://www.agworld.com', 'https://www.agworld.com',
 'freemium', true, 0, 4.0, 650, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['agritech', 'precision-agriculture', 'productivity'],
 ARRAY['Real-time advisor-to-grower recommendation sharing replaces paper scouting reports and phone call delays', 'Mobile-first field data capture with GPS location and photo documentation for professional advisory workflows', 'Shared field history creates documented agronomic record for compliance, audit, and land management decisions', 'Integrates with aerial imagery, soil labs, and accounting systems for comprehensive farm data management'],
 ARRAY['Value is highest when both the advisor and grower actively use the platform - adoption on both sides is required', 'Less suited for farms managed without professional crop advisors or consultants', 'Advanced AI analytics are more limited than field-sensor-focused platforms like Taranis or Climate FieldView', 'Subscription pricing is per advisor seat - costs scale with advisory business size'],
 ARRAY['Agronomic advisory workflow management for crop consulting firms serving multi-farm client portfolios', 'Field scouting data capture and treatment recommendation delivery for commercial row crop operations', 'Audit-ready agronomic record keeping for farms operating under food safety or sustainability certification programs'],
 NOW())

